issue.title: Issues with toplevel domain records and some sort of duplicated subdomain records
issue.body:
Hi,

I'm currently rolling out this webhook to migrate DNS records to desec. While doing so I'm running into 2 issues I'm further debugging:

1. Looks like toplevel domain records like `example.com` do not work. I have enebled that for some service which provides a website including ingress references like `www.example.com` and `example.com` but the webhook fails with something like this: `time="2025-06-30T10:02:04Z" level=error msg="failed to apply changes: 400: body: [{},{},{},{},{\"subname\":[\"This field is required.\"]},{\"subname\":[\"This field is required.\"]},{},{}]"`
2. Every record (in this case it's dummy.example.com) that got to be created because of ingress rules, results in these DNS records and I have currently no idea why, I would expect more or less the TXT records, but no dummy.example records: aaaa-dummy TXT record, a-dummy TXT record, dummy TXT record, dummy.example AAAA record, dummy.example A record, dummy AAAA record and dummy A record

comment.body:
Commit b72bd63408cec659ee15b7869d5483d3f4b9a5ba brings Py-to-MATLAB conversion utilities for various datatypes.  I merged it for the time-being as I don't think I'll be working on this for a short while, but there is still a key point to address which is why I'll be keeping this issue open. This concerns input Data Representation for Save and Integrating with `scipy.io.savemat`.

Since bringing in different representations for MATLAB datatypes like `dictionary`, `containers.Map`, etc. its quite chaotic to manage differences between numpy types and others. Since I'm relying on `scipy.io.savemat` to actually write to file, this means trudging through a `dictionary` looking at each item. It might just be easier to write my own save method, which would simplify a lot of the case handling workflow. 

Some additional points:
- Haven't extensively tested the save methods with MATLAB datatypes
- timetable does not work in MATLAB

pull_request.body:
This pull request introduces Prettier code formatting to the project, adds configuration for automated formatting checks in CI, and includes a new user style for the `tver.jp` website. The most important changes are grouped below:

**Prettier Integration and Automation:**

* Added a Prettier configuration file `.prettierrc` to define code formatting rules for the project.
* Created a `.prettierignore` file to specify files and directories that should be excluded from formatting.
* Updated `package.json` to include Prettier as a dev dependency and added scripts for formatting and checking code style.
* Added a GitHub Actions workflow `.github/workflows/prettier.yml` to automatically run Prettier checks on pull requests targeting the `main` branch.

**New User Style:**

* Added `css/tver.user.css`, a user style for the `tver.jp` website, which increases the maximum width of certain layout containers for a better viewing experience.

Release notes

Sourced from esbuild's releases.

v0.25.8

  • Fix another TypeScript parsing edge case (#4248)

    This fixes a regression with a change in the previous release that tries to more accurately parse TypeScript arrow functions inside the ?: operator. The regression specifically involves parsing an arrow function containing a #private identifier inside the middle of a ?: ternary operator inside a class body. This was fixed by propagating private identifier state into the parser clone used to speculatively parse the arrow function body. Here is an example of some affected code:

    class CachedDict {
  #has = (a: string) => dict.has(a);
  has = window
    ? (word: string): boolean => this.#has(word)
    : this.#has;
}

  • Fix a regression with the parsing of source phase imports

    The change in the previous release to parse source phase imports failed to properly handle the following cases:

    import source from 'bar'
import source from from 'bar'
import source type foo from 'bar'

    Parsing for these cases should now be fixed. The first case was incorrectly treated as a syntax error because esbuild was expecting the second case. And the last case was previously allowed but is now forbidden. TypeScript hasn't added this feature yet so it remains to be seen whether the last case will be allowed, but it's safer to disallow it for now. At least Babel doesn't allow the last case when parsing TypeScript, and Babel was involved with the source phase import specification.

v0.25.7

  • Parse and print JavaScript imports with an explicit phase (#4238)

    This release adds basic syntax support for the defer and source import phases in JavaScript:

    • defer

      This is a stage 3 proposal for an upcoming JavaScript feature that will provide one way to eagerly load but lazily initialize imported modules. The imported module is automatically initialized on first use. Support for this syntax will also be part of the upcoming release of TypeScript 5.9. The syntax looks like this:

      import defer * as foo from "<specifier>";
const bar = await import.defer("<specifier>");

      Note that this feature deliberately cannot be used with the syntax import defer foo from "<specifier>" or import defer { foo } from "<specifier>".

    • source

      This is a stage 3 proposal for an upcoming JavaScript feature that will provide another way to eagerly load but lazily initialize imported modules. The imported module is returned in an uninitialized state. Support for this syntax may or may not be a part of TypeScript 5.9 (see this issue for details). The syntax looks like this:

      import source foo from "<specifier>";
const bar = await import.source("<specifier>");
